item.title: Go travel to flyover states and you’ll get it
item.description: Save the technicalities for the debate competition, I’m calling them flyover states because that’s exactly what they are. Drive through those states (no one fucking flies to them except puddle hoppers) and you’ll see exactly why they would cheer for the destruction of the capitol, and why we are in deeper trouble than we assumed. I drove through Oklahoma, Missouri, Illinois and Indiana over the weekend on interstate highways, and I saw a dozen or so confederate flags on barns and ranches. (I’ve done this exact drive for about 5 years now, and the number of places I feel safe to stop have definitely decreased). I saw more than 1 electronic sign blaming the democrats for the shutdown, in Oklahoma. My favorite sign is from Indiana that claims “no feed because democrat shutdown”, (I’m guessing they mean food for livestock) But I digress, my point being that some of them genuinely see themselves as saviors of America, they draw comparisons to revolutionaries who are destroying the evil govt from the inside. Thats why they see no issues with critiquing the government even when they control pretty much every lever, they are there to destroy it. The govt is currently a hindrance, it’s a safe guard against the their idea of America which is a Christo Fascist state. Destroying the capital means nothing to people who already see it as the Death Star, these are not intelligent people we’re dealing with here. (This was supposed to be a longer rant but I’m no longer is Texas and don’t feel that rant-y, yet. For now I’m a bit too glad to be out of that hell hole)

item.title: Trump's Great Gatsby Party // Behind the meaning. Most things these people do they do to troll their own supporters.
item.description: In The Great Gatsby, Nick Carraway serves as the moral lens through which readers witness the corruption and excess of the wealthy. At first, he is enchanted by the glamour of East Egg, the fictional community representing America’s old-money elite who live in comfort and arrogance across the bay from Gatsby’s mansion. The glittering lights, laughter, and illusion of sophistication draw him in, but as he observes deceit, carelessness, and moral decay, his admiration turns into disgust. By the novel’s end, Nick retreats to the Midwest, disillusioned with a world that confuses wealth for worth. The modern public, too, has become a kind of collective Nick Carraway, once drawn in by the promises of success, freedom, and prosperity, only to discover the emptiness behind the spectacle. Watching a leader celebrate opulence in a Floridian palace while citizens queue for bread mirrors Nick’s awakening: the realization that the dream has been hollowed out, replaced by performance, greed, and indifference. The public’s disillusionment, like Nick’s, is not just disappointment, it is a moral reckoning. The president’s Gatsby party that WoNt KiLl AnYBoDY is not merely a display of ignorance but a calculated act of domination, a performance meant to remind the disillusioned that their despair is part of the show. By recreating the world of Fitzgerald’s moral decay while his citizens suffer, he SNAPS their loss of faith into theater. The so-called hallowed party of conservatism becomes a symbol of mockery, a glittering taunt that says: your hunger feeds my power; your disillusionment is my entertainment. Just as the Buchanans retreated into their wealth after destroying others, this president uses spectacle to assert control, proving that in a society where the dream has died, the ruling class can still profit from the illusion. Everything they do, they do to mock you and America. Destroying the East-Wing? That was to destroy the building FDR built to combat fascism in America and abroad. It was to destroy the building that focused on defeating NAZISM, and combating the effects of a great depression. Franklin D. Roosevelt turned the White House’s East Terrace into the East Wing, building offices and workspaces that let him run the fight against fascism and Nazism. The new wing gave him room for staff, meetings, and communications, making it easier to keep track of global events, coordinate with allies, and plan America’s response to totalitarian threats. It wasn’t just an extension of the house, it was a command center for leading the country through some of the most dangerous years in world history. Eleanor Roosevelt, meanwhile, took over the East Wing in her own way, using it as a stage for activism and to push her progressive agenda. She held gatherings with journalists, politicians, and influential guests, but she didn’t treat them to fancy, indulgent meals. Instead, she served the plainest, cheapest food she could, modeled after what struggling Americans were eating during the Depression, making sure it was as bland and unappealing as possible. It was her sly way of mocking the wealthy, forcing them to sit through a meal that reminded them what ordinary people had to endure, all while she taught about frugality, empathy, and civic responsibility. Attempting to put everything she did into one paragraph is near impossible. They have a Great Gatsby party featuring exotic dancers while pushing fake christian moralities they don't have themselves, it's not by accident. They do this when Americans are starving. It's not an accident. They tear down the building used to defeat Nazis to build a ballroom so they can host parties and dance on the ground they've conquered from within. They did this by taking over a major party. Not creating a Nazi party. They took over a party. They didn't vote third party. They didn't ignore mid-term elections. They didn't say "primaries are pointless." A small amount of Nazis took control of your government by infiltrating a group of morally inept people. YOU CAN DO THE SAME EXACT THING. If you're not voting in mid-term elections--you're doing nothing. If you're not advocating for people in primaries you think are better--you're doing nothing. If you're not aiming for or helping someone obtain organizing positions within the DNC--you're doing nothing.
